description._value: LC-MS untargeted analysis of leaves from two fungus-resistant grape varieties (PIWI) grape varieties (Regent and Phoenix) collected from two countries (Italy and Germany).

All four leaves of each biological replicate were grounded together under nitrogen into a fine homogeneous powder by using mortar and pestle, and then the powder was transferred into falcon tubes and stored at -80 °C until further treatment. 0.5 g of each sample was then weighed into 15 ml amber vials and 50 µL of the internal standard (IS) o-coumaric acid (2 mg/ml MeOH), 1.2 ml of H2O:CH3OH (1:2) and 0.8 ml of CHCl3 were then added. The extraction mixture was vortexed for 1 minute, sonicated for 10 min, shaken for 15 minutes at room temperature using an orbital shaker (Grant-Bio Rotator PTR-60) and centrifuged at 4 °C and 1000g for 10 minutes. 1.5 ml of the upper aqueous methanolic phase was filtered into LC-MS certificated vials through a 0.2 µm filter and analyzed. To avoid bias, the extractions were performed according to a randomized sequence using the sequence calculation platform “www.randomization.org” [1].

Ref:
[1] Ehrhardt C, Arapitsas P, Stefanini M, Flick G, Mattivi F. Analysis of the phenolic composition of fungus-resistant grape varieties cultivated in Italy and Germany using UHPLC-MS/MS. J Mass Spectrom. 2014 Sep;49(9):860-9. PMID: 25230183

A Waters Acquity UPLC (Waters, Manchester, UK) controlled by MassLynx 4.1 was used. All samples were analysed on a reverse phase (RP) ACQUITY UPLC 1.8 µm 2.1 x 150 mm HSS T3 column (Waters) protected with an Acquity UPLC® BEH HSS T3 1.8 µm, 2.1 x 5 mm precolumn (Waters), at 40 °C and under a mobile phase flow rate of 0.28 ml/min. Water was used as weak eluting solvent (A) and methanol as strong eluting solvent (B); formic acid 0.1% v/v was used as additive in both eluents. The multistep linear gradient used was as follows: 0-1 min, 100% A isocratic; 1-3 min, 100-90% A; 3-18 min, 90-60% A; 18-21 min, 60-0% A; 21-25.5 min, 0% A isocratic; 25.5-25.6 min, 0-100% A; 25.6-28 min 100% isocratic. Injection volume was 10 µl, and the samples were kept at 4 °C throughout the analysis [1].

Ref:
[1] Arapitsas P, Speri G, Angeli A, Perenzoni D, Mattivi F. The influence of storage on the “chemical age” of red wines. Metabolomics. Oct 2014, 10(5), 816-832.

Mass spectrometric data were collected by separate runs in positive ESI mode over a mass range of 50 to 2000 amu with scan duration of 0.3 s in centroid mode. The transfer collision energy and trap collision energy were set at 6 V and 4 V. The source parameters were set as follows: capillary 3 kV, sampling cone 25 V, extraction cone 3V, source temperature 150 ºC, desolvation temperature 500 ºC, desolvation gas flow 1000 l/h and nebulizer gas 50 l/h. External calibration of the instrument was performed at the beginning of each batch of analysis by direct infusion of a sodium formate solution (10% formic acid/0.1 M NaOH/Acetonitrile at a ratio of 1/1/8), controlling the mass accuracy from 40 to 2000 m/z (less than 5 ppm) and mass resolution (over 14000 FWHM). LockMass calibration was applied using a solution of leucine enkephaline (0.5 mg/l, m/z 556.2771) at 0.1 ml/min [1].

Ref:
[1] Arapitsas P, Speri G, Angeli A, Perenzoni D, Mattivi F. The influence of storage on the “chemical age” of red wines. Metabolomics. Oct 2014, 10(5), 816-832.
